******
[6] Cholera - Myanmar (Shan): denied
Date: Thu 7 Apr 2011
Source: Democratic Voice of Burma [edited]
http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900sid/SNAA-8FPLZB?OpenDocument&RSS20&RSS20=FS


The UN has said that reports circulating of cholera among victims of
last month's [March 2011] earthquake in Shan state are "absolutely
untrue," although the area has been hit by less severe illnesses.

The Chinese state-run Xinhua news agency claimed that 96 cases of the
contagious illness, 48 of which were serious, had been diagnosed in
the eastern Burmese state, where a 6.8 magnitude quake struck on 24
Mar 2011. It was quoting the Burmese domestic Messenger News journal.

The UN's spokesperson in Burma, Aye Win, told DVB, however, that he
was there at the weekend and no cases had been found, although local
groups had reported "sporadic cases of gastrointestinal diseases and
48 cases of diarrhea." He added that it was "regrettable" that the
false information had been repeated in other news reports, including
the UN's own ReliefWeb service.

