******
[7] Cholera - Philippines (Palawan province)
Date: Thu 14 Apr 2011
Source: Agence France-Presse (AFP) [edited]
http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_656762.html


An outbreak of cholera has killed 19 members of a remote
cave-dwelling Philippine tribe and sickened more than 400 others, the
government said on Thu 14 Apr 2011.

Poor hygiene and the isolation of the Palawanon tribe had made
treatment of the disease difficult, with doctors initially making a
wrong diagnosis of diarrhea, the health department said. The
government agency dispatched a medical team to the island of Palawan
last week to check the outbreak and concluded cholera was to blame,
said Manuel Mapue, the head of the mission.

"The whole area has no potable water system, and there are no
toilets. Being indigenous tribes, these people just defecate
anywhere," he told AFP. He said samples from the rivers used by the
tribe for drinking water showed they were contaminated with feces.

Previous news reports said as many as 30 people had died of the
illness, but a check found only 19 fatalities, said Mr Mapue.

